Identify {= school =}+ schools as degree-granting postsecondary art/design or creative-practice schools, colleges, institutes, academies, conservatories, or named university units; for each school, cover each of the {= surface =} public surfaces listed below by supplying a source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL under each surface) that exposes a concrete surface-specific finding.

The aim is to map how art/design schools publicly present curricular depth, creative admissions expectations, faculty practice, public-facing creative life, and external alumni outcomes.

Public surfaces:
- `degree_program`: the school's curricular public face for a specific creative/art/design degree, program, major, department, or catalog entry
- `admission_portfolio`: applicant-facing creative admissions expectations such as portfolio, audition, artist statement, interview, review, sketchbook, video, SlideRoom, or comparable creative submission material
- `faculty_practice`: a named faculty member's creative, design, scholarly, performance, publication, exhibition, or professional practice as presented through the school
- `public_program`: a dedicated page, or a page section specifically dedicated to one named public-facing creative event, exhibition, show, performance, lecture, visiting-artist program, gallery program, student showcase, or community creative program tied to the school
- `alumni_outcome`: an external-to-school outcome-bearing public surface tying a named alum or former student to a creative, design, scholarly, performance, publication, exhibition, award, role, project, collection, or comparable professional outcome

Schools ought to be real degree-granting postsecondary creative-practice institutions or named school/college-level units, not generic universities submitted without their art/design unit, individual departments or majors, youth camps, museums, galleries, or non-degree workshops. Sources should be fully public, accessible, and usable.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly tie the cited surface to the named school, a named school-affiliated unit, or the school's parent institution.
- The page should make its surface-appropriate role and affiliation visible. For `degree_program`, it should read as an official or institution-controlled program, department, catalog, curriculum, degree, major, or comparable academic page. For `admission_portfolio`, it should read as an official or institution-controlled admissions, portfolio, audition, application-requirement, or applicant-guidance page. For `faculty_practice`, it should read as an official or institution-controlled faculty profile, faculty directory detail, department profile, or faculty-practice story. For `public_program`, it should read as an official, parent-institution, gallery, venue, event-platform, or partner-affiliated page dedicated to one named public program, or a page section specifically dedicated to one named public program. Broad calendars, event indexes, generic public-program landing pages, and pages listing many unrelated events are not sufficient unless the page evidence is anchored to one named program with enough page-role detail. For `alumni_outcome`, it should read as an external-to-school artist/designer profile, portfolio/about page, museum/gallery/collection page, publisher or press page, award/festival page, employer or professional profile, or comparable outcome-bearing surface whose school tie and professional/creative outcome context are visible; generic rankings, admissions-advice pages, broad school lists, school-owned alumni marketing pages, general encyclopedic biographies such as Wikipedia, broad biographical aggregators, and unrelated aggregators are not sufficient when they merely summarize school tie plus notability.
- The page should expose a concrete finding for the selected `surface`: for `degree_program`, a named creative/art/design degree or program plus curriculum, course, concentration, studio, thesis/capstone, credit/unit, learning-outcome, or comparable academic substance; for `admission_portfolio`, a portfolio, audition, creative supplement, artist statement, interview, review, sketchbook, video, SlideRoom upload, or comparable creative application requirement; for `faculty_practice`, a named faculty member plus a creative/design practice, medium, exhibition, publication, performance, professional work, research practice, or comparable practice detail; for `public_program`, a named event, exhibition, show, performance, visiting artist, lecture, gallery program, student showcase, or community creative program plus date, season, venue, public-access, or program-context detail; for `alumni_outcome`, a named alum or former student plus creative/professional outcome detail such as a role, practice, work, project, exhibition, publication, award, collection, performance, company, commission, or comparable post-school achievement on an outcome-bearing external page.
